{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514885"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:27:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:27:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12393"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12393"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.1,0.07,0.06,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107080"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4903"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89544"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"735"},{"type":"tags","id":"1244"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6281"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8054"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107080"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man is brought in by ambulance to the Emergency Department after experiencing a tonic-clonic seizure witnessed by passers-by. He appears stable and his vital signs are within normal limits, but he is clutching his right arm in moderate pain. He has a history of epilepsy, no family history of seizures, and is currently taking sodium valproate long-term. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his right arm is in an adducted and internally rotated position and passive shoulder movement is limited by pain. Sensation is intact and radial pulses are present bilaterally. An AP X-ray of his right shoulder is taken.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following radiological findings would most likely be expected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Light-bulb sign","Hill-Sachs defect","Bankart lesion","Humeral fracture","High-riding humeral head"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the nature of the injury sustained by the patient and the physical findings, the most likely diagnosis is a posterior dislocation of the shoulder. The radiological appearance is often referred to as the \u003Cstrong\u003Elight bulb sign\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as the tennis racket sign). It is the diagnostic radiographic sign of a posterior shoulder dislocation, with a circular appearance of the humeral head (Image). Posterior shoulder dislocation involves internal rotation of the humeral head, which can also have other signs such as reverse Hill-Sachs defect, and reverse Bankart lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHill-Sachs defect\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in a posterolateral depression fracture of the humeral head, caused by impaction of the humeral head on the glenoid rim in an anterior shoulder dislocation. This type of injury involves shoulder external rotation and slight abduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBankart lesion\u003C/strong\u003E is also known as an anteroinferior lesion of the glenoid labrum, which is also seen in an anterior shoulder dislocation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHumeral fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely as it is usually associated with severe local pain, limitation of movement, and typical signs of a fracture such as bruising, swelling, deformity, or extremity shortening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-riding humeral head\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in superior subluxation of the humeral head, which is usually associated with rotator cuff tears rather than posterior shoulder dislocations. It can cause shoulder pain and limited movement as well.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Posterior shoulder dislocation is associated with shoulder internal rotation and adduction, and can be identified on an AP shoulder X-ray with a light bulb sign.","Seizures are a common cause of posterior shoulder dislocations due to the forceful muscle contractions involved."],"references":["Abrams R, Akbarnia H. Shoulder Dislocations Overview. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459125/","Paparoidamis G, Iliopoulos E, Narvani AA, Levy O, Tsiridis E, Polyzois I. Posterior shoulder fracture-dislocation: A systematic review of the literature and current aspects of management. Chin J Traumatol. 2021 Feb;24(1):18-24. doi: 10.1016/j.cjtee.2020.09.001. Epub 2020 Sep 6. PMID: 32980216; PMCID: PMC7878447. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7878447/","Koutserimpas C, Piagkou M, Karaiskos I, Chronopoulos E, Arkoudis NA. Posterior Dislocation of the Shoulder: The Light-Bulb Sign. Cureus. 2023 Oct 27;15(10):e47800. doi: 10.7759/cureus.47800. PMID: 38022099; PMCID: PMC10679799. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38022099/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89544"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12393"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19022"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19022"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/388e636f-2891-40d8-ac3c-c183d2b38116.jpg","thumbUrl":